I know a lot of people have difficulty with holidays and cold weather/winter. My mother did. I do too to a much lesser extent. Please reach out to me, to someone, to anyone.

800-273-8255

But realistically, I think this is the healthiest way I know to grieve her at this time. It sounds trite but my goal is to get people talking, and I think more importantly, get people to listen - actively listen - and if I can, help even one person not to feel like my mother did

But then I worry I am overcompensating for not properly grieving my mother's death (as if there is some way to do that the right way), or that people will think I'm looking for validation from something performative (no one is making me feel that way, just general anxiety)

And I don't mean to shame anyone who struggles with or has suffered any of that in their own lives. I don't shame anyone who struggles with thoughts of suicide or self-harm. What her death has instilled in me is a strong sense wanting to help others

What do you say?

I miss you?

I miss who she was when I was a kid, when I didn't know what bipolar disorder, or schizophrenia, or family dysfunction or codependency was. When I thought that everyone's family acted like mine

To be clear, I am not angry with her for taking her life, just sad for her, sad for my family, and unsure how to process all the rest. It leaves me feeling confused and empty most of the time. I feel like visiting her would be awkward and disingenuous if that makes sense

Many of you may know that my mother and I didn't get along. I hadn't seen her in about 9 years when she passed. The odd thing is her suicide is the most sympathetic I've felt toward her in a long, long time.
